## The bug

`crimes` flags it as **`crime_00010` — Timezone Roulette** at `src/date.ts:29` and `src/date.ts:33`. The relevant function is:

```ts
// src/date.ts:32-34
export function startOfPromoWindow(): Date {
  return new Date("2026-12-20");
}
```

## The literal responsible

**`"2026-12-20"`** — the date-only ISO string at `src/date.ts:33`.

Per the ECMAScript spec, a *date-only* ISO string is parsed as **UTC midnight**, while a datetime *without* a `Z` (like `"2026-12-25T07:00:00"` next door) is parsed as **local time**. Two parsing modes in one file, both flagged by the same finding.

In CI the server is UTC, so the parse "happens" to coincide with the local wall-clock Dec 20 the test author had in mind — the test passes by accident. In any production zone east of UTC, that same Date object is still pinned to `2026-12-20T00:00:00Z`, but every downstream consumer in this file reads it with **local** methods (`getMonth()` at L41, `getDate()` at L41, `toLocaleDateString()` at L46), so the "Dec 20" boundary slides relative to the user's local calendar day.

## Smallest fix (no rename)

Append `T00:00:00` so the literal becomes a zoneless datetime — which ES2015+ parses as **local time**, matching what the UTC CI server was already giving you:

```ts
export function startOfPromoWindow(): Date {
  return new Date("2026-12-20T00:00:00");
}
```

Nine characters added, function name unchanged, no API surface change. Now in *every* environment — CI included — `startOfPromoWindow()` returns "local midnight on Dec 20," which is what the test was implicitly asserting and what each production region needs.

(Adding `Z` instead would be a no-op: date-only literals already parse as UTC, so that wouldn't move production. The fix has to push the parse into local-time mode, not pin it harder to UTC.)
